					<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p>Return to <a href="/wiki/index.php/Microecon:Main" title="Microecon:Main">the list of lectures</a>.
<br /><br />
<strong>The lecture notes are a collaborative effort of the participants in the course. You are not required to contribute to the lecture notes, but are encouraged to do so. Together, we can create resources that will be helpful to everyone.</strong></p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes_for_Week_4:_2.2_Price_Elasticity_of_Demand_and_Revenue">Notes for Week 4: 2.2 Price Elasticity of Demand and Revenue</span></h1>
<p><b>Key words:</b></p>
<ul>
<li>TR is <i>Total Revenue</i></li>
<li>P is Price</li>
<li>Q is Quantity </li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Key Equation:</strong></p>
<p>Total Revenue = Price x Quantity (sold)</p>
<p>TR= PQ</p>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="The_price_elasticity_is_classified_as:_elastic.2C_inelastic_or_unitary.">The price elasticity is classified as: elastic, inelastic or unitary.</span></h2>
<ol>
<li><p>Elastic: The price of demand of a good is larger than 1. (TR decreases)</p></li>
<li><p>Inelastic: The price of demand of a good is smaller than 1. (TR Increase)</p></li>
<li><p>Unitary: The price of demand of a good is equal to 1. (TR stays the same)</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Key concepts:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A change in the price of a good whose demand is inelastic, always generates more revenue. </li>
<li>An increase in price results in an increase in revenue,a decrease in price results in a decrease in revenue (unless the price is elastic).</li>
<li>So the revenue and cost go hand-in-hand. </li>
<li><i>Regarding an elastic demand:</i> An increase in price, generates less quantity of demand for a good, therefore total revenue goes down. And a decrease in the price of this elastic good produces an increased revenue.</li>
</ol>

